New York City
-------------
<http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/doh/html/public/press00/pr78-818.html>
[edited
18 Aug 2000
Three mosquito pools from Staten Island, 1 bluejay from Dongan Hills,
Staten Island, 1 bluejay from Douglaston, Queens and 1 bluejay from Alley
Pond, Queens have tested positive for West Nile virus. All of these areas
were sprayed subsequent to these findings. Additionally, 1 American Kestrel
from Neponsit, Queens, and 1 American Kestrel from Woodside, Queens have
also tested positive for West Nile virus. These findings were reported to
the City Health Department today by the New York State Department of
Health. As a result of this information, the City will apply pesticides to
reduce the number of potentially infected mosquitoes in the 2 areas of
Queens not previously sprayed.
*****
New York State
-------------------
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.htm> [edited
18 Aug 2000
Today, the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Laboratory reported
27 West Nile virus positive dead birds from the following counties:
Clinton, 1; New York City, 5 (Queens 4, Staten Island 1); Onondaga, 3;
Orange, 8; Saratoga, 1; Suffolk, 7 and Westchester 2. Five positive
mosquito pools also were reported: New York City (Staten Island), 4 and
Suffolk County, 1.
The total number of West Nile positive specimens for New York State this
year is 240 birds, 132 mosquito pools, 1 sentinel chicken, 5 live wild
birds and 3 human cases.
Note: The Saratoga and Clinton county birds are the first positive findings
in those counties.
****** Map - WNV Positive Humans, Birds, and Mosquitoes  18 Aug 2000 [JPG
image - 533 KB
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/081800.jpg>
****** [This is a beautifully executed cumulative summary map, showing
numbers of infected humans, birds & mosquito pools in each county, with
lists of species. Congratulations, New York State!  Mod.JW
